PART 2: 2 AND 3 SUBSEQUENCES IN F(n) mod 4
======================================================================

Positions of each residue mod 4 (within period 6):
  F(n) ≡ 0 mod 4: positions mod 6 = [0], first 10: [0, 6, 12, 18, 24]
  F(n) ≡ 1 mod 4: positions mod 6 = [1, 2, 5], first 10: [1, 2, 5, 7, 8, 11, 13, 14, 17, 19]
  F(n) ≡ 2 mod 4: positions mod 6 = [3], first 10: [3, 9, 15, 21, 27]
  F(n) ≡ 3 mod 4: positions mod 6 = [4], first 10: [4, 10, 16, 22, 28]

Decomposition of period {1,1,2,3,1,0}:
  Position 0 (mod 6): F ≡ 0 mod 4 → divisible by 4
  Position 1 (mod 6): F ≡ 1 mod 4 → ≡ 1
  Position 2 (mod 6): F ≡ 1 mod 4 → ≡ 1
  Position 3 (mod 6): F ≡ 2 mod 4 → EVEN, not div by 4
  Position 4 (mod 6): F ≡ 3 mod 4 → ≡ 3
  Position 5 (mod 6): F ≡ 1 mod 4 → ≡ 1

The 2 and 3 are ADJACENT in the period: (2,3) at positions (3,4).
Together they give F(3)×F(4) = 2×3 = 6 = period length!

